<font color="#FF0000">ANSWER TO TOM DIER</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jan  4 11:55:05 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
If I am not mistaken, there were no American combat units in Vietnam at any time while Diem was President of that country.  If I have not been misinformed, Henry Cabot Lodge and Robert McNamara, among other, were responsible for convincing President Kennedy to induce a group of South Vietnamese generals to overthrow and kill Diem and Nhu in 1963.  Furthermore, I know of no protest movement prior to 1963 which demonstrated because the United States had sent military advisors to train the South Vietnamese Army.<br>
It has also been speculated that the main reason Diem was overthrown was because he did not want large American units operating in his country and because he wanted the conduct of the war to remain in Vietnamese hands.<br>
   The United States has supported bloodthirsty dictators in many parts of the world, too numerous to mention, who did things that Diem never could have or would have done.  Yet who has ever protested?  I therefore cannot see any connection whatever between Diem and the Vietnam protest movement.<br>

